Just do:

    map.keySet().retainAll(set);

As per the [javadoc][1], the changes in the key set are reflected back in the map.

&gt; ... The set is backed by the map, so changes to the map are reflected in the set, and vice-versa.  ...

Here&#39;s a demo:

    var map = new HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;();
    map.put(&quot;1&quot;, &quot;one&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;2&quot;, &quot;two&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;3&quot;, &quot;three&quot;);
    
    var set = new HashSet&lt;String&gt;();
    set.add(&quot;1&quot;);
    set.add(&quot;3&quot;);
    
    map.keySet().retainAll(set);
    
    System.out.println(map); // {1=one, 3=three}


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html#keySet()

Elaborating on BalusC&#39;s excellent answer, values() supports retainAll() as well:

    Map&lt;String, String&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;();
    map.put(&quot;1&quot;, &quot;one&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;2&quot;, &quot;two&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;3&quot;, &quot;three&quot;);

    Set&lt;String&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;String&gt;();
    set.add(&quot;one&quot;);
    set.add(&quot;two&quot;);

    map.values().retainAll(set);

    System.out.println(map);   // prints {1=one, 2=two}


retailAll retains duplicate values as well, as you would expect:

    Map&lt;String, String&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;String, String&gt;();
    map.put(&quot;1&quot;, &quot;one&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;2&quot;, &quot;two&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;3&quot;, &quot;three&quot;);
    map.put(&quot;4&quot;, &quot;two&quot;);

    Set&lt;String&gt; set = new HashSet&lt;String&gt;();
    set.add(&quot;one&quot;);
    set.add(&quot;two&quot;);

    map.values().retainAll(set);

    System.out.println(map);  // prints {1=one, 2=two, 4=two}

